    <title>three ring circus</title>
    <content type='html'>&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg3wpZNskoilJtXs7gOuAvFvSMa5k1mt6QTScX0t7GhUWT3QLwjfpxIZCTSC_cyXLfSG2aSVfCLK2wUCq_4PtfhFC7ClTiB8nuWOHVm4j7mBDuqlTaq8c0uPfwv8clb3CmamKgdOXHnCCMt/s1600/rings.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg3wpZNskoilJtXs7gOuAvFvSMa5k1mt6QTScX0t7GhUWT3QLwjfpxIZCTSC_cyXLfSG2aSVfCLK2wUCq_4PtfhFC7ClTiB8nuWOHVm4j7mBDuqlTaq8c0uPfwv8clb3CmamKgdOXHnCCMt/s320/rings.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Just for fun, think about what you see when you look at this diagram. &amp;nbsp;Do you automatically see it as a &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venn_diagram"&gt;Venn diagram&lt;/a&gt; and start thinking about the &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inclusion-exclusion_principle"&gt;principle of inclusion-exclusion&lt;/a&gt;? Maybe if you are more concrete minded, you see it as an &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_diagram"&gt;Euler diagram&lt;/a&gt; and start imagining what concepts or things it might describe (see &lt;a href="http://thisisindexed.com/"&gt;Indexed&lt;/a&gt; for examples, like &lt;a href="http://thisisindexed.com/2010/03/fire-beating/"&gt;this one&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Three circles of equal radius each circle passing through the center of the others provides a ruler and compass construction for an equilateral triangle (ok, you really &lt;a href="http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Geometry_for_Elementary_School/Constructing_equilateral_triangle"&gt;only need two of the circles&lt;/a&gt;, but the third one balances the diagram nicely). &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgoL6Lu03jjq-o5qgthrP1k0hx9QC54pe6qXk4UMhPL4LyoEvLHHI2K2x_pjUbWsePAfX2PC9hgOg2FMX1DH_ufBnrkyB70zLQ-Qake6h3SJeCinNZa-VwMQ81IotK-X5DIXNRV2H8fdAep/s1600/triangle2.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgoL6Lu03jjq-o5qgthrP1k0hx9QC54pe6qXk4UMhPL4LyoEvLHHI2K2x_pjUbWsePAfX2PC9hgOg2FMX1DH_ufBnrkyB70zLQ-Qake6h3SJeCinNZa-VwMQ81IotK-X5DIXNRV2H8fdAep/s200/triangle2.jpg" height="191" width="200" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
If you imagine the circles as rings, you probably imagine the famous &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Borromean_rings"&gt;Borromean rings&lt;/a&gt;, but how many (truly) different ring patterns could you imagine? (See &lt;a href="http://www.liv.ac.uk/~spmr02/rings/types.html"&gt;answer here&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEh9QKIQgTO4RUnym9QnPQ-NYscIrQvLa_w4_dWGvWVewKjjn8vDPQ-g8N-ziS-_wAUCd9JE6r7v1xCIU1F3spQnguOz4D1rf1zwBKs0sSqg4fZlunxtWWR8KSTB7FD3E64cpVsDbXZzKbYR/s1600/rings1.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEh9QKIQgTO4RUnym9QnPQ-NYscIrQvLa_w4_dWGvWVewKjjn8vDPQ-g8N-ziS-_wAUCd9JE6r7v1xCIU1F3spQnguOz4D1rf1zwBKs0sSqg4fZlunxtWWR8KSTB7FD3E64cpVsDbXZzKbYR/s200/rings1.jpg" height="181" width="200" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
And if you look at the center of the diagram, you might see a &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trefoil_knot"&gt;trefoil knot&lt;/a&gt;, or &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triquetra"&gt;triquetra&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;pattern.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhiHZpo4FEecZ3O8O2LSsBJuS7pdajWlQAFMlyAt_-18j_Zcj4vC6YRYzYZS4-yxMG93bB5mozGLi8uWfGmFOz2dNxchZcilHRFRrPm9u49UO2kP6tRNQMMfy8JG2k6JSvBDiUIM7KP1uHq/s1600/triquetta-wikipedia-commons.png" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhiHZpo4FEecZ3O8O2LSsBJuS7pdajWlQAFMlyAt_-18j_Zcj4vC6YRYzYZS4-yxMG93bB5mozGLi8uWfGmFOz2dNxchZcilHRFRrPm9u49UO2kP6tRNQMMfy8JG2k6JSvBDiUIM7KP1uHq/s200/triquetta-wikipedia-commons.png" height="188" width="200" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Trefoils are &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chirality_(mathematics)"&gt;chiral&lt;/a&gt; and can be presented in many different ways - the picture below is also a trefoil (with an opposite 'handedness' to the one above) made using tiles (described a little &lt;a href="http://mathrecreation.blogspot.com/2008/07/knot-tiles.html"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhQwP1TBBfxJf0OuPmv5sJxHQ340PVJWORZoB1cQIxvFzEyS_UHSJs8DaKTyHL5IQzxWJFq4_5t-I-2qGEUoxGYR8e8IrAZV7TTMIicRWaK7XcMkCWutXB37gvhwr7PVb7Xa3S-fp0kln8O/s1600/trefoil2.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhQwP1TBBfxJf0OuPmv5sJxHQ340PVJWORZoB1cQIxvFzEyS_UHSJs8DaKTyHL5IQzxWJFq4_5t-I-2qGEUoxGYR8e8IrAZV7TTMIicRWaK7XcMkCWutXB37gvhwr7PVb7Xa3S-fp0kln8O/s320/trefoil2.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Going back to the original picture, you might be tempted to add more circles and make a nice flower pattern. If you have a mystical mind-set, you might see '&lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flower_of_Life"&gt;the seed of life&lt;/a&gt;' in this diagram.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiA2WTyQQaoEmMUq8uODiqAkrgbP_o4cACaVC92Hy7Q8nvpIQcajavGsdEqULDQYRMm6xjpnDkAPcwjf7oRmYgvlL2BK-e_Xll7qFmAG_6zQLDRRhyphenhyphen0P2QKWza3l8_AtGjFhrpCe1oVPCfw/s1600/flower1.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhZhZeiV8N6Gri1qag3SqzPz8Hz_xjSkELcOhwXPjn9_2J5FvyFw87nCNLpXCPOBJOXCDxA7rLRj_mcfyQ6yRsqabh9ZTxUXY-2_fcd2Sdn8CHtyQjta9kNkJx45tAumtF48ylyVqUDS-NJ/s1600/flower-life-wikipedia-commons.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhZhZeiV8N6Gri1qag3SqzPz8Hz_xjSkELcOhwXPjn9_2J5FvyFw87nCNLpXCPOBJOXCDxA7rLRj_mcfyQ6yRsqabh9ZTxUXY-2_fcd2Sdn8CHtyQjta9kNkJx45tAumtF48ylyVqUDS-NJ/s320/flower-life-wikipedia-commons.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
Alternately, you might see a nice way &lt;a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K8bxVi7OCq0"&gt;to construct a regular hexagon&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEipzizRa4ias8yws7xsUMsI3iFR8kOWoR-aQT6vXtdM7oFV2dkY6aNswEZrpytd2xwtuCWqijx8HuJ29AMNGL9B3iur-pxW9EB2VfLduQpHDyiJKqmROBCaLKeDHQZ3zwiHv0mmNY8FAXhc/s1600/hexagon2.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEipzizRa4ias8yws7xsUMsI3iFR8kOWoR-aQT6vXtdM7oFV2dkY6aNswEZrpytd2xwtuCWqijx8HuJ29AMNGL9B3iur-pxW9EB2VfLduQpHDyiJKqmROBCaLKeDHQZ3zwiHv0mmNY8FAXhc/s320/hexagon2.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
